Each set is of the form \(\{10k + 1, 10k + 2, \ldots, 10k + 10\}\) for \(k\) ranging from 0 to 99. We need to find the number of such sets that contain exactly two multiples of 7. A key observation is that a set \(\{10k + 1, 10k + 2, \ldots, 10k + 10\}\) will have exactly two multiples of 7 if the starting number \(10k + 1\) modulo 7 is 5, 6, or 0. This is because the multiples of 7 in the range \([10k + 1, 10k + 10]\) depend on the remainder when \(10k\) is divided by 7. We solve the congruence \(10k \equiv r \pmod{7}\) where \(r\) must be 4, 5, or 6 for the set to contain exactly two multiples of 7. Since \(10 \equiv 3 \pmod{7}\), we solve: - \(3k \equiv 4 \pmod{7}\) - \(3k \equiv 5 \pmod{7}\) - \(3k \equiv 6 \pmod{7}\) The solutions to these congruences are \(k \equiv 6, 4, 2 \pmod{7}\) respectively. This means for each \(k\), if \(k \equiv 2, 4, 6 \pmod{7}\), the set will contain exactly two multiples of 7. In the range \(k = 0\) to \(99\), there are 14 complete cycles of 7 values (each cycle containing 3 valid \(k\) values: 2, 4, 6) and 2 remaining values. Each cycle contributes 3 sets, leading to \(14 \times 3 = 42\) sets. The remaining 2 values do not contribute any additional sets. Thus, the number of sets containing exactly two multiples of 7 is \(\boxed{42}\).
